## Deployment Steps

### Step 1: Clone the Repository
To ensure your in-app `/api/perform_update` endpoint continues to work, you must use Git to clone the repository rather than manually copying files over FTP.

```bash
cd /var/www/  # Or your preferred hosting directory
git clone https://github.com/pfredz-hsgt/qms-opd3.git qms-opd
cd qms-opd
```

### Step 2: Ensure Required Configuration Exists
Because `serviceAccountKey.json` is typically git-ignored for security, ensure you manually move it to the server.
```bash
# Upload serviceAccountKey.json to the qms-opd directory
```
Ensure the folder permissions allow your executing user (e.g., `ubuntu` or `root`) to create and write to the `logs` folder.
```bash
mkdir logs
chmod 755 logs
```

### Step 3: Install Python Dependencies
It is highly recommended to use a Python virtual environment to avoid conflicts with other system tools.
```bash
# Install venv if you haven't already: sudo apt install python3-venv

# Create and activate virtual environment
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

# Install requirements
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### Step 4: Start the Server with PM2 (Recommended)
You can instruct PM2 to run your Python script using the virtual environment you just created. PM2 will automatically handle keeping the app alive and restarting it when the "Check for Updates" button crashes it.

```bash
# Start the app and name it to be easily recognizable in 'pm2 list'
pm2 start app.py --name "qms-opd" --interpreter ./venv/bin/python

# Save the PM2 process list so it starts on server boot
pm2 save
```

### Step 5 (Optional): Route via Apache
If you want to access the QMS API or WebSocket via a domain name (like `qms.yourdomain.com`) instead of the IP address (e.g., `http://10.77.232.20:5000`), you can set up a reverse proxy using your existing Apache server. Ensure the proxy supports WebSockets (Socket.IO).

Add something like this to your Apache configurations (`/etc/apache2/sites-available/qms.conf`):

```apache
<VirtualHost *:80>
    ServerName qms.yourdomain.com

    # Proxy WebSocket Traffic
    RewriteEngine On
    RewriteCond %{HTTP:Upgrade} websocket [NC]
    RewriteRule /(.*) ws://127.0.0.1:5000/$1 [P,L]

    # Proxy Standard HTTP Traffic
    ProxyPass / http://127.0.0.1:5000/
    ProxyPassReverse / http://127.0.0.1:5000/
</VirtualHost>
```

*(Remember to run `sudo a2enmod proxy_wstunnel proxy_http rewrite` and `sudo systemctl restart apache2` if you implement this).*

